text: Dear Social Justice Warriors, We Asians (the majority of us, anyway) don't give a shit. Why? Because Glen from the Walking Dead is bad ass. We have anime, Sony, ginseng, soy sauce, extremely intuitive and beautiful languages, music which is admittedly a derivative of American pop, skin that barely ages, and more. We don't need you to get upset on our behalf because of a damn movie. Asians make up the majority of the population, but only 5% of the United States' population. So if you have any more BS to say about how this movie is an atrocity for starring a white guy, I'll just tell you that there are other things you should be angry about. Namely DRAGONBALL EVOLUTION and fucking AVATAR THE LAST AIRBENDER!!! Even years later, that wound still burns...  Love, A Korean guy who has confidence in his identity as an Asian and doesn't need some supposedly enlightened loudmouths vehemently protesting what will likely be a trash movie

text: According to Chinese history, the great wall was not entirely built from scratch.   After the Targaryen Empire ... I meant the Qin Empire united the 7 kingdoms around 220BC after hundreds years of Waring States period, they connected the existing walls of several northern kingdoms to form one giant wall.     The purpose was to fend off white walkers...oops I meant Hun raiders.     In the next dynasty, Han Dynasty, massive counter attack of more than 300,000 troops was launched by Han emporer after they were finally fed up with the constant treat from the north.   Chinese record says all wildlings ...Hun male over 15 of age were killed in the counter attack deep into the north.   All remaining huns retreated westward.     The same records claimed these retreating huns eventually reached middle east and Europe...somewhere around Turkey.  And they owned everyone there.   Their number were few, it is propbably how huns were assimilated into local population once they reached middle east and Europe.  The Great Wall you see today was repaired and rebuilt during Ming Dynasty around 1300 to 1600s to defend aganist the Mongols.  Yet, it was the Manchus who eventually breached it after they had Jon Snow... I meant General Yuan Chonghuan killed by his own people in a made up "treason"

text: Most of your guys don't know what is the Great Wall, and what is the monster in the movie. 1. the Great Wall. It is a wall, first built before the Qin Dynasty, BC220. That means, it exists for more than 2,000 years. In the beginning, the Great Wall is used to defend ancient Nomads Of The North. At present, the Wall is a symbol construction of China, just like pyramid to Egypt, Eiffel Tower to France, the Statue of Liberty to US.  2. Ancient China has its own myth system, and most were record in literature. One of the most popular is the Shan Hai Jing (山海经）. Gods, immortals, ghosts and monsters are  included in this book. So, the queen monster in this movie is called Tao Tie, is just a small one.  There is no metaphor in this movie. No Trump, no Mongolians, no Mexican. And, there is no super hero with super power.  Personally, I like this movie, because I like the ancient myth stories. That's all I wanna say.

text: Just watched this movie today, and I really enjoyed it! The cinematography and special effects are breathtaking and every scene is so full of details, and the story's been told beautifully from the start to the end. The plot is simple, but the way it is presented is definitely unlike what you think. The pacing's also well structured for an action fantasy film like this IMO. I initially was skeptical about watching this due to bad reviews and how underwhelming the trailer looked but since it's directed by Zhang Yimou, the same genius who directed the 2008 Beijing Olympic Games' opening ceremony, which was a visual spectacle, plus many other great movies in the past, I had faith in it and thankfully, it did not disappoint at all. So what I wanna say is, ignore the negative reviews and criticisms, especially from people who have not even watched the movie, and go check it out. You'll not regret it!

text: I don't like SJWs and other people who cry race over every little thing but I will agree that from this trailer the film looks bullshit. I like the idea of east meets west historical/fantasy films but this isn't an east meets west film, this is a Chinese fantasy monster flick and they've thrown a white guy in their as the hero, it makes no sense. Do I blame Matt Damon? No he just took a job and will do a better job of it than others, I just don't think the part should have existed in the first place.   If it was a story about some Europeans venturing into China to learn off them then I'd be incredibly interested and if this was just a film about Chinese warriors defending the great wall from Lizard things then I'd be fine with that to. But this is just random and makes no sense.   Please someone just make a decent east meets west film "Outcast" and "Dragon Blade" tried but were filled with bad writing, cheesy humour and overacting or just plain bad acting.

text: For the people that are asking why is  a white man the main character in the movie, you obviously dont know how the film industry works.  A movie cost millions of dollars to produce, this one in particular $150 million. The people that invested that money want their money back and some profit for the risk they took, so they want as many people as humanly possible to go to the movie and spend their $$   Most people go to see a movie not for the movie but cause of the actor that is in the movie. They know that if Tom Hanks, Denzel Washington or Mat Damon is in a movie it is going to be good cause these people are stars and they do not sign up for crappy movies.      If you select  Yang Yang an actor that only a few people outside china know you are going to get a ton of people that are not going to go cause the movie lacks a know star on it. No only that you can go to Zimbabwe and ask  who Mat Damon is and they are going to know, they know he is a good actor, the guys is globally famous... do the same with Yang Yang and tell me what the result will be. No one knows who the fuck he is.     You have to understand movies are made to MAKE MONEY  not for social causes or social justice. And this is why Zhang Yimou a Chinese Director choose Matt Damon over someone that looks  Asian cause he is a smart  film director interested in making his movie as much a success as possible and not some youtube commentator that works flipping burgers at burger king.....

text: Reading all the bad comments and some of the negative reviews, I expected this movie to be mediocre at best. Turns out I've underestimated it. "The Great Wall" was a surprise all the way to finish. I could never actually imagine it would be THIS good. The acting was great, the visuals were amazing, the cinematography was breathtaking, the action were incredible and Jing Tian's beauty was totally stunning. There were several times  I was on the edge of my seat holding breath anticipating the next moment. I really don't remember myself feeling such an amount of excitement during the movie for a long time and it was obvious that everyone who was watching it in the cinema with me felt the same. Overall, I would rate it 9/10, minus point for the running time - it's way too short lol. For everyone who is considering whether to watch this movie or not - ignore the noise of negative people. Let them get sick with their views. Give "The Great Wall" a chance and enjoy it to the fullest! Just like what the characters said : "Trust"! My personal recommendation would be to watch it in 3D/IMAX and Dolby Atmos sound if possible for even better experience :)
